T1  - The Knowledge-Leveraging Paradox: How to Achieve Scale without Making Knowledge Imitable
AU  - Coff, Russell W.
AU  - Coff, David C.
AU  - Eastvold, Roger
Y1  - 2006/04/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2006.20208690
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2006.20208690
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 452
EP  - 465
VL  - 31
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Tacit knowledge, one of the most promising resources, is among the toughest toleverage. It is important because it is often inimitable. However, increasing its scalemay require codification, which may make it imitable. We explore and illustrate anapproach to applying information technologies to leverage scarce expertise withoutcodifying or transferring knowledge. Such technology may allow individuals to furtherspecialize and generate more tacit knowledge, preserving the strategic propertiesof knowledge while scaling up.
AB  - Tacit knowledge, one of the most promising resources, is among the toughest toleverage. It is important because it is often inimitable. However, increasing its scalemay require codification, which may make it imitable. We explore and illustrate anapproach to applying information technologies to leverage scarce expertise withoutcodifying or transferring knowledge. Such technology may allow individuals to furtherspecialize and generate more tacit knowledge, preserving the strategic propertiesof knowledge while scaling up.
